Since universal elements are initial, the colimit
  D\xrightarrow {\lambda } \operatorname *{colim} D of a diagram J\xrightarrow {D} C is
  initial in the category of elements \text {el}(\operatorname *{Cocone}_D),
  in the sense that for any other cocone
  D\xrightarrow {\mu } c, there exists a unique map \operatorname *{lim} D\to  c so that each of
  the following triangles commute:




    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
  \usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

  \tikzset{
    % basics
    square/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=4},
    triangle/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=3},
  }

  \tikzset{
    % string diagrams
    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
